#compdef besticon
# =============================================================================
# besticon — Matthias Lüdtke's "Favicon service written in
#          Go" — a long-standing Go-native favicon
#          finder + extractor that takes a URL and
#          returns the best-quality icon associated
#          with the target site, scraping the
#          `<head>` of the rendered HTML for every
#          `<link rel="icon">`, `<link rel="apple-
#          touch-icon">`, `<meta name="msapplication-
#          TileImage">`, etc., plus the well-known
#          `/favicon.ico` fallback path.  Originally
#          built to power Lüdtke's
#          besticon.herokuapp.com favicon-as-a-service
#          + the open-source IconHorse / Statically-
#          serving-icons stack.
#          Distinguishing from `google/favicon?domain=
#          example.com` (Google's icon service —
#          opaque + frequently returns generic globes),
#          DuckDuckGo's `/ip3/example.com.ico` icon
#          endpoint (also third-party hosted),
#          IconHorse (a hosted competitor), and naive
#          curl-of-favicon.ico approaches (which miss
#          all the modern multi-size apple-touch-icon
#          variants) by:
#            - HTML-FIRST DISCOVERY — scrapes the
#              rendered HTML head section using
#              PuerkitoBio/goquery v1.12 (this is the
#              headline CLI library that CONTINUES
#              Axis 41 on the Go side; see taxonomy
#              notes below) to find every declared
#              `<link>` icon reference; doesn't
#              merely fetch /favicon.ico and hope
#            - MULTI-SIZE AGGREGATION — collects ICO/
#              PNG/SVG/JPG variants across all
#              declared sizes (16x16, 32x32, 192x192,
#              512x512, apple-touch-icon-180x180,
#              etc.), then ranks them by area and
#              format quality to pick the BEST one
#            - SIZE-RANGE QUERY — `besticon` CLI's
#              backing library supports a "give me
#              the icon closest to 32px" query via
#              `besticon.ParseSizeRange` (used by the
#              iconserver companion); CLI mode
#              defaults to returning the largest/
#              best icon URL
#            - ICO PARSER — bundled `ico/` package
#              parses the legacy multi-resolution
#              .ico container format (which embeds
#              multiple PNGs/BMPs into one file)
#              and extracts individual frames
#            - LETTERICON FALLBACK — bundled
#              `lettericon/` package generates a
#              colorful single-letter icon when the
#              target site has NO icon at all
#              (e.g. `https://example.org/letter/
#              E.png`); served by the iconserver in
#              fallback mode
#            - COLORFINDER — bundled `colorfinder/`
#              package extracts the dominant color
#              from an icon image, used by
#              lettericon to pick a background color
#              that visually matches the site brand
#            - GROUPCACHE — uses golang/groupcache
#              for cross-instance distributed cache
#              of fetched icons; suitable for
#              horizontally-scaled iconserver
#              deployments behind a load balancer
#            - PROMETHEUS METRICS — iconserver mode
#              exposes /metrics for Prometheus
#              scraping (icon-fetch rate, cache hit
#              ratio, error counts)
#            - CORS-AWARE — iconserver wraps responses
#              with rs/cors for browser-side fetch()
#              integrations; useful as a backend for
#              SPA dashboards that need favicons
#            - TWO BINARIES IN ONE MODULE:
#              * `besticon` — CLI client that emits
#                the best icon URL for a given URL
#              * `iconserver` — HTTP service that
#                exposes besticon as REST/JSON API +
#                HTML demo page; configured via env
#                vars (PORT, ADDRESS, CACHE_SIZE_MB,
#                HOST_ONLY_DOMAINS, SERVER_MODE)
#            - 988+ STARS ON mat/besticon — long-
#              standing maintenance since 2015;
#              currently on v3 (go.mod uses module
#              path github.com/mat/besticon/v3)
#          Used by: web app developers who need to
#          embed favicons for arbitrary external
#          URLs (bookmark managers, RSS readers,
#          link-aggregator dashboards, browser
#          start-pages), browser-extension authors
#          showing icons for currently-open tabs,
#          marketing platforms displaying brand
#          icons for client domains, and any
#          context where Google's google/favicon
#          service is too unreliable.
#
# Author:  Matthias Lüdtke (mat on GitHub;
#          https://better-idea.org).  Based in Hamburg,
#          Germany; software engineer at XING (LinkedIn
#          competitor in Germany); previously
#          @dynport / @phrase / @crealytics.
# Source:  https://github.com/mat/besticon
#          https://github.com/mat/besticon/blob/master/besticon/besticon/cmd.go
#          https://github.com/mat/besticon/blob/master/besticon/iconserver/server.go
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `besticon` with no
#          args prints a usage message (positional URL
#          + --all flag).  Full docs in repo README.md.
# Library: github.com/PuerkitoBio/goquery v1.12.0 —
#          Martin Angers's "Like jQuery, in Go" library
#          (this is the headline dependency for this
#          completion's axis-41 continuation role; see
#          taxonomy notes below).  Also Go stdlib's
#          flag (Axis 1 argparse), net/http (HTTP
#          fetching), encoding/json + image/{png,gif,
#          jpeg} (decoder), golang.org/x/image (image
#          format extensions), golang.org/x/net/html
#          (transitive via goquery), golang/freetype
#          (font rendering for lettericon),
#          prometheus/client_golang v1.23 (metrics for
#          iconserver), rs/cors v1.11 (CORS for
#          iconserver), groupcache (distributed cache).
# License: MIT
# Status:  988+ stars on mat/besticon; active
#          maintenance (latest commit 2026-05-26);
#          v3.x release line under module path
#          `github.com/mat/besticon/v3`.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY — AXIS 41 CONTINUES:
#   HTML PARSING / WEB SCRAPING (Go side)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# This completion **CONTINUES AXIS 41** in the cross-
# language CLI library taxonomy.  R753 Rust=96 (email-
# sleuth/scraper OPENS Axis 41) → R754 Go=96 (besticon/
# PuerkitoBio/goquery CONTINUES Axis 41 THIS ROUND).
# Pending: R755 TS-Node=96 with a cheerio user to close
# Axis 41 at 1/1/1.
#
# WHY PuerkitoBio/goquery IS A DISTINCTIVE AXIS-41
# CONTINUATION:
#
#   github.com/PuerkitoBio/goquery by Martin Angers is
#   the de-facto Go HTML parsing + CSS-selector library
#   — explicitly modeled on jQuery's API for Go
#   programmers familiar with web-frontend traversal
#   idioms.  Distinguishing characteristics:
#     1. JQUERY-INSPIRED API — `doc.Find("div.contact-
#        list > a.email")`, `.Each`, `.Attr`, `.Text`,
#        `.Children`, `.Parent`, `.Siblings`, etc.
#        match jQuery's method names + semantics
#        precisely; learning curve is nearly zero for
#        anyone who has used jQuery
#     2. golang.org/x/net/html FOUNDATION — built on
#        the Go team's official HTML5-compliant
#        tokenizer from the golang.org/x/net/html
#        package; gets the same WHATWG-compliant
#        recovery rules used internally by Go's
#        net/http (when parsing HTML for rendering)
#     3. CSS-SELECTOR LIBRARY (andybalholm/cascadia)
#        — goquery delegates selector parsing to
#        Andy Balholm's cascadia package, which
#        supports the full CSS3 selector grammar
#        including pseudo-classes (`:not()`,
#        `:has()`, `:nth-child()`, etc.)
#     4. STREAMING-CAPABLE — supports parsing from
#        io.Reader (not just []byte), allowing
#        large pages to be parsed without buffering
#        the full document in memory
#     5. ~14,500+ STARS ON PuerkitoBio/goquery
#     6. UNIVERSAL GO ECOSYSTEM USAGE — used by
#        gocolly/colly (the dominant Go scraping
#        framework, already in corpus as _colly),
#        besticon (this completion), mindoc, sun-
#        panel, proxypool, mangodl, j3ssie/
#        goverview, mat/besticon (this), thousands
#        of other Go scraping projects
#     7. PROVEN SINCE 2012 — Martin Angers
#        (PuerkitoBio) created the library in
#        December 2012 against Go 1.0; it has
#        evolved alongside Go's stdlib HTML parser
#        without breaking API
#
# Maintained under github.com/PuerkitoBio/goquery.
# License: BSD-3-Clause.
#
